{"questionId":"27623","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math>, for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>The graph of a linear function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is parallel to the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> and passes through the&nbsp;origin. Find an expression for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>gradient of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math> (may be seen in function, do not accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math>)<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></math><em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </strong></em><em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27623","referenceCode":"22N.1.SL.TZ0.1a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The graph of a linear function g is parallel to the graph of f and passes through the origin. Find an expression for g(x).","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaV